{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Open your web browser and navigate to https://git-scm.com/downloads. This official site usually detects your operating system automatically and highlights the relevant download link.",
      "title": "Visit the Download Page"
    },
    {
      "text": "Click the \"Download\" button for your operating system. For Windows, save the .exe file. For macOS, choose the binary installer if you are not using a package manager like Homebrew.",
      "title": "Download the Installer"
    },
    {
      "text": "Locate the downloaded file in your Downloads folder and double-click it to launch the setup wizard. On macOS, you may need to open the .pkg file contained within the downloaded disk image.",
      "title": "Run the Installer"
    },
    {
      "text": "Click through the installation prompts. For beginners, the default settings are recommended. Keep clicking \"Next\" to accept the defaults until you reach the actual installation step.",
      "title": "Follow the Setup Wizard"
    },
    {
      "text": "Click \"Install\" and wait for the progress bar to complete. Once finished, click \"Finish\" or \"Close\" to exit the installer. You may uncheck \"View Release Notes\" if asked.",
      "title": "Complete the Installation"
    },
    {
      "text": "To confirm Git is working, open your command line tool. On Windows, search for and open \"Git Bash\" from the Start menu. On macOS or Linux, open the \"Terminal\" application.",
      "title": "Open Command Line"
    },
    {
      "text": "Type `git --version` and press Enter. You should see a response like \"git version 2.x.x\". If you see this version number, Git is successfully installed and ready to use.",
      "title": "Verify Installation"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Ensure the vehicle is on a flat, hard surface. Shift into Park (or First Gear for manual) and firmly engage the emergency brake. Turn on your hazard lights to alert passing traffic.",
      "title": "Secure the Vehicle"
    },
    {
      "text": "Place wheel wedges, heavy rocks, or bricks in front of and behind the tires on the opposite side of the car from the flat tire. This prevents the car from rolling while lifted.",
      "title": "Block the Wheels"
    },
    {
      "text": "Get your jack and lug wrench from the trunk. If your wheels have hubcaps covering the nuts, use the tapered end of the lug wrench to pry the cover off so the nuts are exposed.",
      "title": "Expose the Lug Nuts"
    },
    {
      "text": "Fit the lug wrench onto a nut and turn counter-clockwise. Apply force to break the resistance, loosening it about one full turn. Repeat for all nuts, but do not remove them yet.",
      "title": "Loosen Lug Nuts"
    },
    {
      "text": "Locate the designated jacking point under the car frame near the flat tire (check your manual if unsure). Slide the jack under this reinforced spot ensuring it sits flat on the ground.",
      "title": "Position the Jack"
    },
    {
      "text": "Turn the jack handle clockwise to raise the car. Continue lifting until the flat tire is approximately 6 inches (15 cm) off the ground and spins freely.",
      "title": "Raise the Vehicle"
    },
    {
      "text": "Unscrew the loosened lug nuts the rest of the way by hand or with the wrench. Place the nuts together in a secure spot, like your pocket or inside the hubcap, so they aren't lost.",
      "title": "Remove Lug Nuts"
    },
    {
      "text": "Grip the tire by the treads with both hands. Pull the tire straight toward you until it slides completely off the hub bolts.",
      "title": "Remove the Tire"
    },
    {
      "text": "Lay the flat tire on the ground. For added safety, slide it under the side of the vehicle near the jack. This acts as a cushion if the jack slips while you grab the spare.",
      "title": "Set Aside the Flat"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Bring fresh water to a boil, then remove it from the heat source. Let it sit for about 30-60 seconds to reach the optimal temperature of 200°F (93°C). Boiling water can scorch the coffee beans.",
      "title": "Heat the Water"
    },
    {
      "text": "Measure 30 grams (about 4 tablespoons) of coarse coffee grounds. Add them to the bottom of your empty French press. The grounds should look like coarse sea salt.",
      "title": "Measure and Add Grounds"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pour just enough hot water over the grounds to wet them completely. Wait 30 seconds. You should see the coffee bubble and rise—this is called the \"bloom.\"",
      "title": "Bloom the Coffee"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pour the remaining hot water into the press until full. Use a spoon to gently stir the top crust of coffee to ensure all grounds are fully saturated.",
      "title": "Fill and Stir"
    },
    {
      "text": "Place the lid on the carafe with the plunger pulled all the way up. Do not press down yet. Set a timer for 4 minutes to allow the coffee to steep.",
      "title": "Cover and Steep"
    },
    {
      "text": "After 4 minutes, slowly and steadily push the plunger down to the bottom. Keep the rod vertical. If you feel too much resistance, lift the plunger slightly and resume pressing.",
      "title": "Plunge the Coffee"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pour the coffee into mugs or a separate carafe right away. Do not let the coffee sit in the press with the grounds, or it will continue extracting and become bitter.",
      "title": "Pour Immediately"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Remove all weeds, large rocks, and debris from your selected planting spot. Ensure the area is completely clear to prevent competition for nutrients. The soil surface should be bare and accessible.",
      "title": "Clear the Planting Area"
    },
    {
      "text": "Use a digging fork or spade to turn the soil to a depth of at least 12 inches (30 cm). Break up any hard clumps or compacted earth. Tomatoes have deep roots, so the soil must be loose and crumbly.",
      "title": "Loosen the Soil"
    },
    {
      "text": "Spread a 2-to-3-inch layer of aged compost or organic manure over the top of your loosened soil. This organic matter improves drainage and provides essential nutrients for the growing season.",
      "title": "Add Organic Matter"
    },
    {
      "text": "Sprinkle a balanced vegetable fertilizer (like 5-10-5) over the compost layer. Add a handful of bone meal or crushed eggshells per plant spot to provide calcium, which helps prevent blossom end rot.",
      "title": "Apply Tomato Fertilizer"
    },
    {
      "text": "Use your fork or shovel to turn the soil again, blending the compost and fertilizer thoroughly with the native soil. Ensure the amendments are mixed in to a depth of 6 to 8 inches.",
      "title": "Mix Ingredients Thoroughly"
    },
    {
      "text": "Use a garden rake to smooth the surface of the soil. Break up any remaining small clumps and level the bed. The final texture should be fine and even.",
      "title": "Rake and Level"
    },
    {
      "text": "Water the prepared bed gently until the soil is moist about 6 inches deep, but not soggy. Let the soil settle for a day or two before planting to ensure the nutrients begin to activate.",
      "title": "Water to Settle"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Clear a large, flat surface like a table. Lay your ironed fabric out completely flat, right side up. Smooth out any wrinkles with your hands to ensure accurate measurements.",
      "title": "Prepare Your Workspace"
    },
    {
      "text": "Using a measuring tape, measure 45 inches along the fabric's long edge (selvage). Mark this length clearly with tailor's chalk or a fabric pen. This length accommodates a standard pillow plus the hem.",
      "title": "Mark the Length"
    },
    {
      "text": "From your length mark, measure 21 inches perpendicular to the selvage edge. Use a yardstick or clear ruler to ensure a perfect 90-degree angle. Mark this point.",
      "title": "Mark the Width"
    },
    {
      "text": "Connect your marks using a straight edge to draw a full rectangle (45\" x 21\") on the fabric. Press firmly enough with the chalk so the lines are clearly visible for cutting.",
      "title": "Draw the Cutting Lines"
    },
    {
      "text": "Place pins just inside your drawn lines, spaced about 6 inches apart. This helps keep the fabric layers stable and prevents shifting while you cut.",
      "title": "Pin for Stability"
    },
    {
      "text": "Using sharp fabric shears, cut precisely along your chalk lines. Keep the bottom blade of the scissors gliding on the table surface to support the fabric and ensure a straight, clean cut.",
      "title": "Cut Along the Lines"
    },
    {
      "text": "Remove the pins and inspect your fabric rectangle. Check that the edges are straight and smooth. You should now have a single rectangular piece ready for pinning and sewing.",
      "title": "Inspect the Cut Piece"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Turn on your electronic tuner or open a tuning app. If using a clip-on tuner, attach it securely to the guitar's headstock. Ensure the tuner is set to 440Hz standard tuning mode (often labeled 'C' for Chromatic or 'G' for Guitar).",
      "title": "Prepare Your Tuner"
    },
    {
      "text": "Locate the thickest string, which is closest to your face. This is the 6th string. Trace it up to the headstock to identify exactly which tuning peg controls it.",
      "title": "Identify the Low E String"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pluck the 6th string clearly. Watch the tuner display. If the needle is to the left (flat), tighten the string. If it's to the right (sharp), loosen it. Adjust until the tuner indicates a centered 'E' (often turning green).",
      "title": "Tune the Low E"
    },
    {
      "text": "Move to the 5th string (the next one down). Pluck it and adjust its corresponding tuning peg until the tuner displays a centered 'A'.",
      "title": "Tune the A String"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pluck the 4th string. Adjust the peg until the tuner reads 'D'. Make sure you are turning the peg connected to this specific string.",
      "title": "Tune the D String"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pluck the 3rd string. Tune it to 'G'. Be careful with your adjustments, as thinner strings are more sensitive to tension changes.",
      "title": "Tune the G String"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pluck the 2nd string. Tune it to 'B'. If the tuner fluctuates, mute the other strings with your hand to ensure it only hears the B string.",
      "title": "Tune the B String"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pluck the thinnest string (1st string), closest to the floor. Tune it to 'E'. This is the highest pitch string.",
      "title": "Tune the High E String"
    },
    {
      "text": "Play each string again from Low E (thickest) to High E (thinnest). Tension changes can pull earlier strings slightly out of tune. Make final micro-adjustments until every string reads perfectly in tune.",
      "title": "Verify All Strings"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Turn on your camera and remove the lens cap. Ensure you have a subject in front of you and adequate lighting to practice exposure settings.",
      "title": "Prepare Your Camera"
    },
    {
      "text": "Rotate the mode dial on the top of your camera to \"M\". You should see an \"M\" indicator appear on your LCD screen or inside the viewfinder, confirming you are in Manual Mode.",
      "title": "Switch to Manual Mode"
    },
    {
      "text": "Press the ISO button or navigate to ISO settings in your menu. Select ISO 400 as a starting point. This offers a good balance for general indoor or outdoor lighting.",
      "title": "Set Baseline ISO"
    },
    {
      "text": "Locate the aperture dial (often a wheel near the shutter button). Rotate it until you see f/5.6 on your display. This is a standard aperture that keeps most subjects in focus.",
      "title": "Set the Aperture"
    },
    {
      "text": "Look through the viewfinder or at the LCD screen for the exposure scale. It resembles a ruler with a \"0\" in the center, a \"+\" side (overexposed), and a \"-\" side (underexposed).",
      "title": "Locate the Light Meter"
    },
    {
      "text": "Rotate the shutter speed dial while watching the light meter. If the indicator is on the \"-\" side, slow the speed down. If it is on the \"+\" side, speed it up. Stop when the mark aligns with \"0\".",
      "title": "Balance the Exposure"
    },
    {
      "text": "Press the shutter button halfway to lock focus, then press fully to take the shot. Wait for the image to be recorded to the memory card.",
      "title": "Capture the Image"
    },
    {
      "text": "Press the Playback button to inspect your photo. If the image is too dark, lower your shutter speed. If it's too bright, increase it. Repeat until the image brightness looks natural.",
      "title": "Review and Adjust"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Stand with your feet slightly wider than shoulder-width apart. Point your toes slightly outward (about 5 to 15 degrees). Ensure your weight is evenly distributed across your whole foot, from heel to toe.",
      "title": "Set Your Stance"
    },
    {
      "text": "Stand tall and pull your shoulders back and down to puff out your chest. Tighten your abdominal muscles as if you are bracing for a punch. This neutral spine position protects your lower back.",
      "title": "Engage Core and Posture"
    },
    {
      "text": "Begin the movement by pushing your hips backward, as if you are reaching for a chair behind you. Do not start by bending your knees forward; the hips must move back first.",
      "title": "Initiate With Hips"
    },
    {
      "text": "Bend your knees to lower your body, keeping your chest up and back straight. Lower yourself until your thighs are at least parallel to the floor. If your heels lift off the ground, don't go quite as low.",
      "title": "Lower Your Body"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pause briefly at the bottom. Glance down to ensure your knees are tracking in line with your toes and not collapsing inward. Your knees should not extend excessively past your toes.",
      "title": "Check Knee Alignment"
    },
    {
      "text": "Push firmly through your heels to return to a standing position. Keep your chest up as you rise. Squeeze your glutes at the top to complete the rep, ensuring your hips are fully extended.",
      "title": "Drive Up to Stand"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Tenha à mão 500g de farinha de trigo, 300ml de água morna, 10g de fermento biológico seco, 10g de sal e uma pitada de açúcar. Deixe tudo na bancada antes de começar.",
      "title": "Separe os Ingredientes"
    },
    {
      "text": "Em uma tigela pequena, misture a água morna, o açúcar e o fermento. A água deve estar morna ao toque (como mamadeira), não fervendo.",
      "title": "Misture o Fermento"
    },
    {
      "text": "Deixe a mistura de fermento descansar por 5 a 10 minutos. Você verá uma espuma cremosa se formar na superfície, indicando que o fermento está ativo.",
      "title": "Aguarde a Ativação"
    },
    {
      "text": "Enquanto o fermento ativa, coloque a farinha e o sal em uma tigela grande. Misture bem para que o sal não entre em contato direto e concentrado com o fermento depois.",
      "title": "Misture os Secos"
    },
    {
      "text": "Faça um buraco no centro da farinha e despeje a mistura de fermento já espumada. Use uma colher ou as mãos para misturar até que a farinha absorva todo o líquido.",
      "title": "Incorpore os Líquidos"
    },
    {
      "text": "Polvilhe um pouco de farinha sobre uma superfície limpa e lisa. Vire a massa da tigela sobre esta superfície para começar a trabalhar nela.",
      "title": "Transfira para a Bancada"
    },
    {
      "text": "Empurre a massa para frente com a base da palma da mão, dobre-a sobre si mesma e gire-a 90 graus. Repita esse movimento ritmado para desenvolver o glúten.",
      "title": "Comece a Sovar"
    },
    {
      "text": "Continue sovando por 10 a 15 minutos. Se a massa estiver muito grudenta, adicione farinha aos poucos, mas evite o excesso para não deixar o pão duro.",
      "title": "Sove até Alisar"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pare de sovar quando a massa estiver lisa, elástica e desgrudando das mãos. Pressione com o dedo: se a massa voltar rapidamente, o ponto está correto.",
      "title": "Verifique o Ponto"
    },
    {
      "text": "Modele a massa em uma bola lisa, tensionando a superfície para baixo. Isso ajuda a manter o formato durante o crescimento.",
      "title": "Boleie a Massa"
    },
    {
      "text": "Unte levemente a tigela com óleo, coloque a bola de massa dentro e cubra com um pano úmido ou plástico filme para evitar que resseque enquanto descansa.",
      "title": "Prepare para o Descanso"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Busca las válvulas debajo del fregadero y gíralas a la derecha hasta que se detengan. Si no las ves, cierra la llave general de la casa. Abre el grifo para vaciar el agua restante de la tubería.",
      "title": "Cierra el paso de agua"
    },
    {
      "text": "Coloca el tapón o un trapo viejo sobre el orificio del desagüe. Esto evitará que tornillos o piezas pequeñas caigan por la tubería accidentalmente mientras trabajas.",
      "title": "Protege el desagüe"
    },
    {
      "text": "Si tu grifo tiene tapas decorativas (marcas de frío/caliente), usa un destornillador plano pequeño o una navaja para levantarlas con cuidado y dejar expuesto el tornillo interno.",
      "title": "Retira la tapa del mango"
    },
    {
      "text": "Usa un destornillador para quitar el tornillo que sujeta el mango. Tira de la manija hacia arriba para sacarla. Si está atascada, muévela suavemente de lado a lado hasta que ceda.",
      "title": "Desatornilla la manija"
    },
    {
      "text": "Usa una llave inglesa o pinzas ajustables para aflojar la tuerca que sostiene el vástago o cartucho en su lugar. Gira hacia la izquierda (contra las manecillas del reloj) y retírala.",
      "title": "Quita la tuerca de sujeción"
    },
    {
      "text": "Saca el vástago (la pieza interna) tirando hacia arriba. Examina la arandela de goma en la base o las juntas tóricas (anillos de goma negros). El desgaste o rotura aquí suele ser la causa de la fuga.",
      "title": "Extrae el vástago o cartucho"
    },
    {
      "text": "Quita la arandela vieja destornillándola o corta las juntas tóricas gastadas. Instala los repuestos nuevos exactos. Si el cartucho entero se ve dañado o con mucho sarro, reemplázalo por uno nuevo idéntico.",
      "title": "Reemplaza las piezas dañadas"
    },
    {
      "text": "Inserta el vástago reparado en el cuerpo del grifo. Vuelve a enroscar la tuerca de sujeción, coloca la manija y aprieta el tornillo superior. Finalmente, presiona la tapa decorativa en su lugar.",
      "title": "Reensambla el grifo"
    },
    {
      "text": "Quita el trapo del desagüe. Abre lentamente las válvulas de paso debajo del fregadero. Abre el grifo para liberar aire y luego ciérralo. Observa la base y la boca del grifo para confirmar que ya no gotea.",
      "title": "Restablece el agua y prueba"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Locate the \"File\" tab or menu in the top-left corner of the application window. Click it to reveal the main menu options.",
      "title": "Open the File Menu"
    },
    {
      "text": "Click on \"Save As\" from the list of options. Even if you click \"Save\" on a new document, the program will usually open the \"Save As\" dialog so you can name the file.",
      "title": "Select Save As"
    },
    {
      "text": "Choose the folder where you want to store your file, such as \"Documents\" or \"Desktop.\" You may need to click a \"Browse\" button to see your computer's folder structure.",
      "title": "Choose a Location"
    },
    {
      "text": "Click inside the \"File name\" box. Type a descriptive name for your document so you can easily identify it later.",
      "title": "Enter a File Name"
    },
    {
      "text": "Click the \"Save\" button, usually located at the bottom-right corner of the dialog box. The dialog box will close.",
      "title": "Click Save"
    },
    {
      "text": "Look at the title bar at the very top of the window. It should now display the specific name you just typed, confirming the document has been saved successfully.",
      "title": "Verify the Save"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Clear a large, non-conductive surface like a wooden table. Gather a Phillips head screwdriver (usually size #2) and your components. Ground yourself by touching a metal object or wearing an anti-static wrist strap to prevent static damage.",
      "title": "Prepare Your Workspace"
    },
    {
      "text": "Take the motherboard out of its anti-static bag and place it on top of its cardboard box. This provides a safe, non-conductive platform for installing the CPU and RAM before placing the board into the tight space of the case.",
      "title": "Prepare the Motherboard"
    },
    {
      "text": "Lift the retention arm on the CPU socket. Align the golden triangle on the CPU corner with the triangle on the socket. Gently place the CPU in—do not force it. Lower the retention arm and lock it under the tab. The plastic protective cover will pop off automatically.",
      "title": "Install the CPU"
    },
    {
      "text": "Push down the tabs on the RAM slots. Align the notch on the RAM stick with the ridge in the slot. Press down firmly on both ends of the stick until you hear a click and the tabs snap back into place to lock the module.",
      "title": "Install RAM Modules"
    },
    {
      "text": "If your cooler lacks pre-applied thermal paste, apply a pea-sized amount to the center of the CPU heat spreader. Mount the cooler according to its specific manual (using screws or clips). Plug the fan cable into the header labeled 'CPU_FAN'.",
      "title": "Mount the CPU Cooler"
    },
    {
      "text": "Remove the side panels of your case. If the I/O shield is not pre-installed on the motherboard, snap the metal plate into the rectangular cutout at the back of the case. Ensure the brass standoffs inside the case match your motherboard's mounting holes.",
      "title": "Prepare the Case"
    },
    {
      "text": "Lower the motherboard into the case, angling it so the rear ports fit through the I/O shield. Align the screw holes with the standoffs. Fasten the motherboard securely using the supplied screws, but be careful not to overtighten.",
      "title": "Install the Motherboard"
    },
    {
      "text": "Slide the Power Supply Unit (PSU) into its mount, usually at the bottom-rear of the case. Secure it with four screws from the outside back of the case. Route the cables through the back panel openings to keep the main chamber tidy.",
      "title": "Install the Power Supply"
    },
    {
      "text": "Plug the large 24-pin cable into the right side of the motherboard. Find the 4-pin or 8-pin CPU power cable (labeled CPU or EPS) and plug it into the connector near the CPU socket at the top left of the board.",
      "title": "Connect Main Power Cables"
    },
    {
      "text": "For M.2 drives, screw them into the motherboard slots now. For SATA SSDs/HDDs, mount them in the drive bays or sleds. Connect the SATA data cables to the motherboard and the SATA power cables from the PSU to the drives.",
      "title": "Install Storage Drives"
    },
    {
      "text": "Remove the expansion slot covers on the back of the case corresponding to the top PCIe x16 slot. Unlock the slot's plastic tab. Push the GPU into the slot until it clicks, then secure the metal bracket to the case with screws.",
      "title": "Install the Graphics Card"
    },
    {
      "text": "Locate the PCIe power cables (often labeled VGA or PCIe) from your PSU. Plug the required 6-pin or 8-pin connectors into the power ports on the side or top of your graphics card.",
      "title": "Connect GPU Power"
    },
    {
      "text": "Consult your motherboard manual for the front panel diagram. Connect the small cables for Power Switch, Reset, and LEDs to the correct pins. Connect the USB and Audio headers to the matching ports on the bottom edge of the motherboard.",
      "title": "Wire Front Panel Headers"
    },
    {
      "text": "Check that all cables are fully seated and fans are unobstructed. Bundle excess cables using zip ties. Reattach the case side panels. Connect the power cord to the wall, flip the PSU switch to 'I', and press the power button to test.",
      "title": "Perform Final Check"
    }
  ]
}
